"""
MKT Context — 1 Samuel chapters 9–12
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-1samuel-9-12.py

Ch9:  Saul's donkey search, meeting Samuel at the high place (27 verses)
Ch10: Saul anointed, signs fulfilled, prophesying, public selection at Mizpah (27 verses)
Ch11: Ammonite siege of Jabesh-gilead, Saul's rescue, covenant renewal at Gilgal (15 verses)
Ch12: Samuel's farewell address — covenant lawsuit (rib) genre, historical recital (25 verses)

Key context themes:
- Iron Age I rural economy: donkeys as significant property
- Seers (roeh) vs. prophets (nabi) — terminological transition
- High places (bamot) as legitimate pre-centralization cult sites
- Oil anointing as ANE royal inauguration rite
- Ecstatic prophecy guilds; Mari texts parallels
- Lot-casting (Urim/Thummim) as legitimate divination in Israel
- Mishabat hammeleḵ — written royal covenant limiting kingship
- Nahash the Ammonite — Transjordanian geopolitics, right-eye gouging as mutilation-tactic
- Herem-solidarity threat: cutting oxen = covenant-cutting oath-enforcement
- Gilgal as key covenant-renewal site in Iron Age Israel
- rib (covenant lawsuit) genre in Samuel's farewell address
- Wheat harvest thunder as seasonal divine sign
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / f'mkt-{source}' / f'{book}.json'
    return json.loads(p.read_text()) if p.exists() else {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / f'mkt-{source}' / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

CONTEXT = {
  "9": {
    "1": "<p>Kish is introduced with a five-generation genealogy — Benjaminite, son of Abiel, Zeror, Bechorath, Aphiah. Iron Age I genealogies served social and legal functions: establishing tribal membership, land tenure rights, and marriage eligibility. The descriptor <em>gibbôr ḥayil</em> (man of valor/substance, also used for Boaz in Ruth 2:1) indicates wealth, military standing, and social prominence — Kish is not a marginal figure but an established clan head whose family would have been expected to provide military leadership in the tribal levy system.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Saul is described as <em>ṭôḇ wĕyāp̄eh</em> (good and handsome) with a height advantage — a head taller than anyone in Israel. Physical stature carried political significance in the ancient Near East: height was associated with divine favor, military prowess, and royal bearing. Egyptian royal iconography routinely depicted pharaohs towering over courtiers and enemies. The Ugaritic Keret epic similarly emphasizes the king's imposing physical presence. Saul's height will be mentioned again in 10:23 as the crowd's affirmation; it is a cultural marker of leadership capacity, not merely personal description.</p>",
    "3": "<p>Donkeys (<em>ʾătōnôṯ</em>) were primary livestock in Iron Age I Canaan — used for transport, plowing, and trade. Their loss would constitute a significant economic setback for a household. A landowner of Kish's status sending his son on a search indicates the animals' value; this was not a trivial errand. The instruction to take a servant (<em>naʿar</em>) reflects elite social structure where household servants accompanied family members on extended travel — the servant's practical knowledge (9:6) and financial resources (9:8) show this is a trusted household aide rather than a menial laborer.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The search route through the hill country of Ephraim, Shalisha, Shaalim, and the Benjaminite territories covers approximately 40-50 miles of central highland terrain. Iron Age I highland Israel was a landscape of scattered villages, terraced agriculture, and forest-covered ridges — the terrain made animal searches genuinely difficult. The regions named are the central Benjamin-Ephraim highlands, a zone of dense village settlement in the archaeological record of the 12th-11th centuries BCE. The three-day circuit (implied by 9:20: &#8220;lost three days ago&#8221;) was the standard duration of a search expedition.</p>",
    "5": "<p>Zuph is the region associated with Samuel's family (1:1: Elkanah is an Ephraimite from Ramathaim-zophim, i.e., the Zuph region). Saul's concern about his father's anxiety reflects Iron Age family dynamics — adult sons were expected to report back within predictable timeframes, and prolonged absence created genuine anxiety before any search infrastructure existed. The servant's local knowledge of the &#8220;man of God&#8221; in the nearby town shows how prophetic figures functioned as regional resources: known by name across villages and consulted for practical needs including lost property.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The servant describes Samuel as <em>ʾîš ʾĕlōhîm nikkāḇāḏ</em> (man of God, highly honored) — the <em>ʾîš ʾĕlōhîm</em> title designates a divine messenger with direct access to divine knowledge and power (used for Moses in Deut 33:1, Elijah in 1 Kgs 17:18, Elisha throughout 2 Kgs). The phrase &#8220;all he says comes true&#8221; (<em>kōl ʾăšer yĕdabbēr bōʾ yāḇôʾ</em>) applies the Deuteronomic criterion for prophetic authority (Deut 18:22) as his regional reputation: his track record of fulfilled words has spread beyond Shiloh into the surrounding villages.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Saul's concern about gift-protocol for consulting a prophet reflects ANE practices of fee-payment to seers and diviners. In Mesopotamian texts, divination specialists (bārûm, āšipu) received standardized fees — animals, silver, grain, oil — for their services. The Mari archive documents extensive payments to prophetic figures. In Israel, consulting a seer normally involved a gift; the exchange was not commercial but honorific — acknowledging the divine source of the knowledge while sustaining the prophet's household. Saul's empty-handed state creates a social awkwardness that the servant resolves.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The quarter shekel (<em>rĕḇîaʿ haššeqel</em>) of silver in the servant's possession was a modest but adequate consultation fee. Iron Age I Israel used a weight-based silver economy without coins — silver was measured by shekel weights (8.4 grams standard). A quarter shekel (about 2 grams of silver) represented roughly a day's wage or a small livestock purchase. The servant's &#8220;I happen to have&#8221; (<em>nimṣāʾ bĕyāḏî</em>) suggests incidental possession — not prepared specifically for this consultation, but sufficient for the social protocol.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The narrator's parenthetical explains a terminological shift: the older term <em>rōʾeh</em> (seer, from <em>rāʾāh</em>, to see) was being replaced in the narrator's own time by <em>nāḇîʾ</em> (prophet). This shift reflects a historical process: the earlier seer tradition (associated with ecstatic vision, oracular knowledge, practical divination) was absorbed into the broader prophetic movement of the 10th-9th centuries BCE. The narrator preserves the older term as a historical note for his later audience. ANE parallels: Mesopotamian <em>mahhu</em> (ecstatic) and <em>apilu</em> (answerer) functioned similarly to the rōʾeh — accessing divine knowledge for practical inquirers.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Saul's acceptance of the servant's suggestion and their movement toward the town models how Iron Age Israelites navigated the intersection of practical need and religious resource. The consultation of prophets/seers for lost property, crop failure, illness, and military decisions was normalized behavior — not exceptional religiosity. The Mesha Stele (9th century, Moab) and Zakkur inscription (8th century, Hamath) both document rulers consulting prophetic figures for military guidance. Samuel's role as regional seer-consultant is the localized expression of a broadly attested ANE pattern.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The young women drawing water (<em>nĕʿārôṯ yōṣĕʾôṯ lišʾōḇ māyim</em>) outside the town gate represent the standard daily labor of Iron Age village women. Water-drawing was a female responsibility in the household economy, typically done in the late afternoon before cooking (cf. Gen 24:11; Exod 2:16). The town gate was the public information hub of Iron Age villages — news, legal proceedings, and social exchanges centered there. Saul's inquiry at the gate zone follows the natural social logic of the era: approach the first people you meet near the town boundary for local information.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The women's response confirms Samuel's presence in town for a <em>zāḇaḥ</em> (sacrificial feast) at the high place. The <em>bāmāh</em> (high place, pl. <em>bāmôṯ</em>) was a cultic installation typically on an elevated feature near a town — altars, sacred stones (maṣṣēḇôṯ), and sometimes small structures. High places were legitimate worship sites throughout the pre-Solomonic period; the Deuteronomistic critique of high places (1 Kgs 3:2-3) reflects later centralization theology. The women's urgency (&#8220;hurry&#8221;) reflects the meal protocols: the blessing preceded eating and the seer's arrival determined the feast's start time.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The feast logistics described (sacrificial blessing must precede eating; invited guests await the man of God) reflect Iron Age sacrificial meal protocols. Communal <em>zebaḥ šĕlāmîm</em> (peace/fellowship offerings) involved killing and partial burning of an animal, with the meat shared among participants after priestly preparation. The invited thirty guests represent the social network of a regional prophetic center — elders, leaders, and dignitaries from the area who would share the sacred meal under Samuel's blessing. The high-place feast was as much a social institution as a religious one.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The narrative's visual scene — Saul and servant entering the town just as Samuel exits toward the high place — is constructed with dramatic irony: YHWH has engineered the collision of the two parties. The gate zone (<em>šaʿar</em>) was the commercial, legal, and social center of Iron Age towns. Archaeological excavations at Iron Age I sites (Megiddo, Dan, Beersheba) reveal multi-chambered gates with benches where civic life concentrated. The encounter at this threshold location is spatially deliberate: the gate is where destinies intersect in Israelite narrative.</p>",
    "15": "<p>&#8220;YHWH had disclosed (<em>gālāh ʾet ʾōzen</em>, lit. uncovered the ear of) Samuel the day before Saul arrived.&#8221; The idiom &#8220;uncover the ear&#8221; is the intimate whisper of a superior to a subordinate — the physical act of bending close and removing hair or cloth to speak privately. In Iron Age culture, direct divine communication was understood as a rare privilege; the day-in-advance disclosure establishes that Saul's arrival is not coincidence but divine orchestration. Samuel has been waiting, already knowing what YHWH has prepared to announce.</p>",
    "16": "<p>YHWH's commission uses <em>nāgîḏ</em> (ruler/designated leader) rather than <em>melek</em> (king) — a significant distinction. <em>Nāgîḏ</em> designates one who is set before the people as YHWH's representative leader; the term appears in military, administrative, and priestly contexts throughout the OT (2 Sam 5:2; 1 Kgs 1:35; 1 Chr 9:11). YHWH frames Saul's designation in covenantal terms: he will save Israel from the Philistines because YHWH has seen the people's suffering (<em>rāʾîṯî ʾet-ʿammî</em>) — echoing the Exodus pattern (Exod 3:7: &#8220;I have indeed seen the misery of my people&#8221;). The Philistine threat was the political crisis driving the monarchy transition.</p>",
    "17": "<p>YHWH's direct identification of Saul to Samuel — &#8220;here is the man I told you about&#8221; (<em>hinnēh hāʾîš ʾăšer ʾāmartî ʾēlêḵā</em>) — confirms the correspondence between the prior divine disclosure and the present encounter. The phrase &#8220;he will govern my people&#8221; (<em>hûʾ yaʿṣōr bĕʿammî</em>) uses <em>ʿāṣar</em> (to restrain/govern/rule) — a term that emphasizes the limiting and ordering function of rule rather than unlimited sovereignty. YHWH's framing of the king as one who governs &#8220;my people&#8221; keeps the ultimate ownership of Israel with YHWH; the king is steward, not sovereign.</p>",
    "18": "<p>Saul asks Samuel for directions to the &#8220;seer's house&#8221; (<em>bêṯ hārōʾeh</em>) — using the older term the narrator has just explained (9:9). This is a small but theologically loaded moment: Saul is seeking the seer not knowing the seer already knows him. Iron Age prophetic households functioned as institutions: a seer of Samuel's stature would have had a residence identifiable by townspeople, a regular schedule of consultations, and a known fee structure. The casual inquiry at the gate for directions to his house reflects this normalization of prophetic consultation in village life.</p>",
    "19": "<p>Samuel's self-disclosure (&#8220;I am the seer&#8221;) followed by an invitation to ascend to the high place for the meal and a promise of disclosure &#8220;all that is in your heart&#8221; overturns Saul's entire purpose. He came for information about donkeys; he receives an invitation to a royal feast. The high place meal was a formal, covenantally significant occasion — not a casual dinner. Samuel's invitation positions Saul as the guest of honor at a sacred feast, a social elevation that the narrative will explain only retrospectively. The promise &#8220;tomorrow I will send you on your way&#8221; establishes an overnight stay — a full hosting relationship.</p>",
    "20": "<p>Samuel's disclosure that the donkeys have been found is a double prophetic signal: it demonstrates his knowledge of distant events (validating his seer status for Saul) and removes the practical obstacle of Saul's mission. The pivot to &#8220;And as for all that is desirable in Israel — is it not for you and your whole father's house?&#8221; is the first royal oracle, delivered obliquely. Iron Age political communication often used indirection and ambiguity for sensitive disclosures — Saul's confusion in v21 confirms he has not grasped the full import. Samuel is planting a seed before the formal anointing the next day.</p>",
    "21": "<p>Saul's demurral — &#8220;But I'm a Benjaminite, from the smallest tribe&#8221; — follows the OT pattern of the called one's resistance (Moses: Exod 3:11; Gideon: Judg 6:15; Jeremiah: Jer 1:6). The claim that his family is &#8220;the least of all the clans of Benjamin&#8221; may be sincere humility or conventional protestations. Benjamin's tribal status was ambiguous: the tribe was nearly annihilated in the civil war of Judges 19-21, making it numerically smallest. However, Kish's genealogy (9:1) and his <em>gibbôr ḥayil</em> status suggest genuine social standing, not marginal origins. The disclaimer is the appropriate posture before elevation.</p>",
    "22": "<p>Samuel brings Saul and his servant into the <em>liškat</em> (banquet chamber, a side room attached to the cultic installation) and seats them at the &#8220;head of the invited guests&#8221; — approximately thirty men. The guest-of-honor positioning is a formal social signal in Iron Age feast culture; seating at the head communicated rank and honor before words did. The number thirty may reflect a standard assembly quorum for regional civic-religious gatherings. The servant's inclusion at the honored table (rather than separate lower seating) shows Samuel extending the honor to Saul's entire household unit.</p>",
    "23": "<p>The reserved portion — set aside by Samuel before Saul arrived — demonstrates pre-knowledge. ANE sacrificial protocol distinguished between the portions burned for the deity, the priestly portions, and the portions distributed to participants. Samuel had instructed the cook to set aside a specific portion — likely the thigh, associated with honor and priestly privilege in Israelite ritual (Lev 7:32-34: the thigh goes to the officiating priest). Reserving a distinguished portion for an unnamed future guest required prophetic foreknowledge; the cook's compliance without explanation shows Samuel's household authority.</p>",
    "24": "<p>The cook sets before Saul the thigh and its accompanying portion, and Samuel explains: &#8220;Look, what was kept is set before you — eat, because it was kept for you for this appointed time.&#8221; The word <em>môʿēd</em> (appointed time/meeting) carries covenantal weight throughout the OT — the tent of meeting (<em>ʾōhel môʿēd</em>) uses the same root. Samuel is framing this meal as a divinely appointed occasion rather than a chance encounter. The honor of the thigh portion at the feast is a public signal to the thirty guests that this Benjaminite stranger is being designated for something significant.</p>",
    "25": "<p>The rooftop conversation (<em>wayyĕdabbēr ʿim-šāʾûl ʿal-haggāg</em>) between Samuel and Saul reflects Iron Age domestic architecture. Flat mudbrick roofs were functional spaces for sleeping in hot weather, drying grain, and private conversation. The roof provided relative privacy from household activity below. That Samuel chose the roof for this conversation signals the intimacy and privacy of what is being discussed — the designation of a king was politically sensitive information requiring confidential communication before public announcement. The roof-as-private-space is used similarly in 2 Sam 11:2 (David's rooftop observation of Bathsheba).</p>",
    "26": "<p>The dawn departure scene — Samuel calling up to Saul on the roof at first light — reflects Iron Age travel culture. Long-distance travel typically began at dawn to maximize daylight hours and avoid midday heat. Samuel's early awakening of Saul and their simultaneous arising establishes the urgency of the day's purpose. The phrase &#8220;I will send you on your way&#8221; (<em>šallaḥtiḵā</em>) echoes the covenant-dispatch language used for prophets and messengers. The edge-of-town location for the private anointing (v27) moves the ceremonial act out of the public gate zone into a liminal space.</p>",
    "27": "<p>The dismissal of the servant to go ahead — &#8220;but you, stand still for the moment so I may make known to you the word of God&#8221; — creates a private dyadic moment for the anointing. The phrase <em>dĕḇar ʾĕlōhîm</em> (word of God) frames what follows as divine oracle, not personal opinion. The edge of town was legally and socially liminal in Iron Age culture — neither inside the town's communal protection nor outside in the open countryside. Prophetic acts often occurred in liminal spaces: thresholds, edges, crossroads. The private anointing at the town's edge corresponds to the not-yet-public nature of Saul's designation.</p>"
  },
  "10": {
    "1": "<p>Samuel takes a <em>pak haššemen</em> (flask of oil) and pours it over Saul's head — the inauguration anointing. Oil anointing as royal installation rite appears throughout the ancient Near East: Egyptian coronation texts describe the anointing of vassal kings; the Amarna letters reference oil as a symbol of royal appointment; Ugaritic texts describe divine anointing of the king. In Israel, the anointing was the constitutive act of becoming <em>māšîaḥ</em> (anointed one) — the act that transferred divine authority to the person for the designated office. The kiss that follows the anointing is a covenant-sealing gesture acknowledging the new relationship between the prophet (as YHWH's agent) and the anointed king.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The first sign — meeting two men at Rachel's tomb near Zelzah in Benjamin — grounds the prophetic confirmation in a geographically specific location. Rachel's tomb at the border of Benjamin (identified with the region of Bethlehem/Ramah in later tradition; cf. Gen 35:19-20; Jer 31:15) was a landmark site carrying ancestral memory. The two men's message (donkeys found; father worried about Saul) confirms Samuel's prior knowledge and demonstrates YHWH's coordination of events. The sign functions as a divine authentication: when you encounter exactly what I described, you will know the designation is real.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The oak of Tabor (location uncertain, possibly in the Bethel region of central Benjamin) is the site of the second sign — three men going to Bethel with offerings. The three men carry animals, bread, and wine — the standard components of a sacrificial offering meal at a sanctuary. Their offering of two loaves to Saul is unprompted from Saul's side; the strangers' gift functions as an unexpected token of what YHWH is initiating. The three-sign structure of the prophecy (vv2-6) reflects ANE prophetic authentication patterns: multiple confirmatory events whose precise alignment eliminates coincidence.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The acceptance of bread from the three strangers is framed as receiving from YHWH's hand — the travelers are unknowing agents of divine provision. In Iron Age travel culture, receiving food from strangers was both a practical necessity and a social bond; the gift established hospitality obligations. The specific number &#8220;two of their loaves&#8221; ensures the detail is precise enough to be unmistakable when it occurs. Samuel's instructions treat Saul as a passive recipient in this phase of his initiation — he is to accept what comes to him rather than initiate or direct.</p>",
    "5": "<p>Gibeah-elohim (&#8220;hill of God&#8221;) is associated with the presence of a Philistine garrison (<em>neṣîḇ pĕlištîm</em>) — an administrative or military post indicating Philistine control of this strategic highland location. Iron Age I Philistine expansion from the coastal plain into the central highlands is attested archaeologically at sites like Beth-Shean and Megiddo. The presence of a group of prophets (<em>ḥeḇel nĕḇîʾîm</em>) with instruments — lute, tambourine, flute, harp — and descending from the high place represents the ecstatic prophetic bands known in the early monarchy period. The coincidence of Philistine garrison and prophetic community at the same location suggests prophetic activity as a form of resistance or counter-cultural presence under occupation.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The promise that the Spirit of YHWH will &#8220;come powerfully upon&#8221; (<em>ṣālaḥ ʿālêḵā rûaḥ YHWH</em>) Saul, causing him to prophesy, parallels the Spirit-bestowal language used for judges (Judg 3:10; 6:34; 11:29; 14:6). The phrase &#8220;you will be changed into a different person&#8221; (<em>nĕhāpakṯā lĕʾîš ʾaḥēr</em>) — using <em>hāpak</em> (to overturn/transform) — is the language of radical reversal. This transformation is not psychological but functional: the Spirit's coming equips for the office. The connection between Spirit-empowerment and prophetic ecstasy is attested in ANE texts: Mari prophets (muhhum) underwent altered states during oracular delivery.</p>",
    "7": "<p>&#8220;Act as the situation demands&#8221; (<em>ʿăśēh lĕḵā ʾăšer timṣāʾ yāḏeḵā</em>, lit. do for yourself what your hand finds) is the standard idiom for spontaneous, circumstance-driven action in Israelite narrative (cf. Judg 9:33; Eccl 9:10). The phrase &#8220;for God is with you&#8221; (<em>kî hāʾĕlōhîm ʿimmāk</em>) is the assurance formula given to those YHWH has designated for a task — the same formula given to Joshua (Josh 1:9), David (2 Sam 7:3), and later to Jeremiah (Jer 1:8). Samuel is commissioning Saul with the standard prophetic authentication of divine presence.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The instruction to go to Gilgal and wait for Samuel for seven days connects Saul's inauguration to the covenant site. Gilgal (near Jericho in the Jordan Valley) was a primary Israelite covenant-renewal site: the first Passover in Canaan was celebrated there (Josh 5:9-12), the memorial stones from the Jordan crossing were erected there, and it remained a major cultic center throughout the early monarchy. Seven-day waiting periods were standard ritual durations in Israel and throughout the ANE — the completion of a ritual cycle. The burnt offerings and fellowship offerings Samuel promises to make at Gilgal would formalize the covenant between YHWH and the new king.</p>",
    "9": "<p>&#8220;God gave him a new heart&#8221; (<em>wayyahăpāk-lô ʾĕlōhîm lēḇ ʾaḥēr</em>) — the same <em>hāpak</em> root used in v6 (&#8220;changed into a different person&#8221;) is now applied to the inner transformation. The heart (<em>lēḇ</em>) in Israelite anthropology was the seat of will, decision-making, and moral orientation — not merely emotion. The divine gift of a new heart anticipates the Ezekiel 36:26 &#8220;new heart&#8221; promise; YHWH's action at this point is the supernatural preparation of Saul for kingly function. That all the signs came to pass validates the prophetic word and demonstrates the coherence of divine action in history.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The arrival at the hill (Gibeah-elohim from v5) where the prophets meet Saul, and the Spirit of God coming upon him powerfully, triggers the predicted ecstatic prophesying. The prophetic band (<em>ḥeḇel nĕḇîʾîm</em>) in Iron Age Israel functioned as organized communities around a prophetic leader, using music to induce and accompany ecstatic states — paralleling the Mari prophetic communities and similar groups in Phoenician cult (cf. the Baal prophets on Carmel in 1 Kgs 18:26-29). Saul's Spirit-induced joining of the group demonstrates that the divine empowerment is genuine and publicly visible.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The question &#8220;What happened to the son of Kish? Is Saul also among the prophets?&#8221; (<em>hagam šāʾûl bannĕḇîʾîm</em>) reflects the social incongruity of a wealthy landowner's son prophesying with the ecstatic bands. The prophetic groups occupied a socially ambiguous status — respected as channels of divine power but also viewed as socially marginal or disruptive. Saul's social position (son of a <em>gibbôr ḥayil</em>) made his participation in ecstatic prophesying surprising; it crossed the social boundary between elite and prophetic-band culture. The question becomes a proverbial saying, preserved as such by the narrator.</p>",
    "12": "<p>&#8220;And who is their father?&#8221; — the rhetorical question challenges any assumption that prophesying was confined to particular lineages or social classes. The prophetic Spirit cannot be predicted by ancestry; its bestowal is sovereign. The saying &#8220;Is Saul also among the prophets?&#8221; (<em>hagam šāʾûl bannĕḇîʾîm</em>) became proverbial — used in 19:24 of the same phenomenon in a different context. Proverbial sayings in the OT often encode social observations about paradoxes and incongruities; this one captures the surprise when the Spirit crosses expected social boundaries.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Saul's departure from the prophetic band and his going to the high place completes the cycle of the signs Samuel predicted. The movement from town entry to prophesying to high place reflects the geographic-ritual pattern of the day: the prophets descend from the high place (v5), Saul encounters them, the Spirit comes, he prophesies, then moves to the high place. The high place (<em>bāmāh</em>) is the cultic endpoint of the sequence — the space where YHWH's presence was accessed and where covenantal acts were performed.</p>",
    "14": "<p>Saul's uncle (possibly Ner, father of Abner — cf. 14:50-51) meets Saul and asks where he went. The uncle's inquiry reflects the social monitoring function of the extended family in Iron Age Israel — household heads tracked the movements and activities of family members for security, reputation, and economic reasons. Saul's report: &#8220;We went looking for the donkeys — and then went to Samuel&#8221; gives the factual account without interpretation. His uncle's pointed follow-up (v15) — &#8220;Tell me what Samuel said to you&#8221; — indicates that a consultation with Samuel was sufficiently significant to warrant detailed reporting.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The uncle's pressing question about Samuel's words reflects the understood significance of prophetic oracles in Iron Age Israel. A consultation with Samuel — the nationally recognized prophet and judge — was not ordinary private business; a family member receiving an oracle from Samuel would be expected to disclose it. The social expectation was that prophetic words of significance affecting the family or tribe would be shared within the household. The uncle's insistence is proportionate to his understanding of Samuel's authority and the potential implications for the family.</p>",
    "16": "<p>Saul's selective disclosure — reporting that the donkeys were found but not mentioning the kingship — is a studied concealment. The phrase &#8220;the matter of the kingship he did not tell him&#8221; (<em>ûdĕḇar hammalḵûṯ lōʾ-higgîḏ lô</em>) signals Saul's discretion at this stage of the process. Whether from modesty, uncertainty, or deliberate concealment, Saul guards the oracle's content. This restraint will be visible again at his public selection (10:22: hiding among the baggage). The narrator notes the concealment to signal that the kingship designation is still private; its public announcement will come through the lot-casting at Mizpah.</p>",
    "17": "<p>Samuel assembles Israel at Mizpah (<em>hammiṣpāh</em>) for the public selection. Mizpah was a primary covenant-assembly site in Benjamin — the location of the earlier assembly that initiated the war against Benjamin (Judg 20:1), and a cultic center where Samuel regularly judged Israel (7:5-16). Its association with communal assembly, covenant-making, and divine decision-making made it the appropriate venue for the public kingship installation. The assembly &#8220;before YHWH&#8221; (<em>lip̄nê YHWH</em>) frames the event as a covenant-making occasion in the divine presence, not merely a political election.</p>",
    "18": "<p>Samuel's historical recital beginning with the Exodus (&#8220;I brought Israel up out of Egypt, and I rescued you from the hand of Egypt and of all the kingdoms that oppressed you&#8221;) positions the monarchy transition within the framework of YHWH's saving acts. The pattern — YHWH as actor, Israel as recipient of salvation — is the covenant-history recital genre attested in Deut 26:5-9, Josh 24:2-13, and Ps 105-106. The purpose is to frame the present moment against the background of YHWH's faithfulness, establishing the covenantal basis before announcing the covenant's new institutional form.</p>",
    "19": "<p>&#8220;But today you have rejected your God — the one who has saved you from every calamity and distress — and you have said, &#8216;No, set a king over us.'&#8221; The <em>rîb</em> (covenant lawsuit) pattern — reciting YHWH's benefits followed by Israel's failure — is the standard prophetic accusation structure (cf. Mic 6:1-5; Jer 2:5-13; Isa 1:2-4). Samuel's framing of the kingship request as &#8220;rejection of YHWH&#8221; (<em>mĕʾastĕm YHWH</em>) is the theological interpretation established in ch8. The use of &#8220;today&#8221; (<em>hayyôm</em>) gives the accusation present-tense urgency: the rejection is not past but ongoing.</p>",
    "20": "<p>The tribe-by-tribe lot selection uses the same procedure as the Achan identification (Josh 7:14-18): tribes presented, one selected by lot, then clans, then households, then individuals. The <em>gôrāl</em> (lot) mechanism in Israel was understood as disclosing YHWH's decision, not random chance — Prov 16:33: &#8220;the lot is cast into the lap, but its every decision is from YHWH.&#8221; Benjamin's selection as the tribe continues the pattern of the unlikely tribe providing the initial king — Benjamin was the smallest and most recently devastated tribe (Judges 19-21), making its selection a divine demonstration of sovereign choice over human expectation.</p>",
    "21": "<p>The clan of Matri (otherwise unattested in OT genealogies) is selected, then Saul son of Kish — and Saul cannot be found. The lot proceeds to its conclusion; the selection is unmistakable. Lot-casting to identify individuals was used throughout ANE legal and cultic contexts — Hittite oracle texts, Mesopotamian extispicy, and Ugaritic divination texts all attest to the use of lots for divine identification. The public nature of the selection process — witnessed by all assembled Israel — ensures the legitimacy of the choice and removes the possibility of human manipulation of the outcome.</p>",
    "22": "<p>The inquiry &#8220;has the man arrived yet?&#8221; (<em>hăbāʾ ʿôḏ hălōm hāʾîš</em>) followed by YHWH's response that he has hidden among the baggage (<em>hannê hûʾ nĕhbāʾ ʾel-hakkēlîm</em>) is a comic-ironic moment: the king-elect is hiding. The baggage or equipment (<em>kēlîm</em>) typically included tents, provisions, and military supplies brought by the assembled tribal contingents. The hiding could reflect genuine modesty, ambivalence, or the same reticence shown in v16. YHWH's disclosure of the hiding place via oracle is the final divine confirmation — even Saul's location is known to YHWH and can be revealed through the established prophetic channel.</p>",
    "23": "<p>When retrieved from hiding, Saul's height is again noted — he stands a head taller than everyone (cf. 9:2). The public display of his physical impressiveness is a concession to the popular desire for visible kingship: the people wanted a king &#8220;like all the nations,&#8221; and their ideal king was visually impressive. The narrator records the height both as historical fact and as ironic setup — the tall, impressive king will ultimately fail; the short shepherd boy of ch16 who &#8220;does not look on outward appearance&#8221; will be the genuine king. Height as a royal qualifier is deconstructed over the course of Samuel's narrative.</p>",
    "24": "<p>Samuel's presentation — &#8220;Do you see who the LORD has chosen? There is no one like him in all Israel&#8221; — uses the language of divine election (<em>bāḥar</em>, H977) that will later be applied to David (2 Sam 6:21; Ps 78:70). The people's response — <em>yĕḥî hammelek</em> (&#8220;Long live the king!&#8221;) — is the standard royal acclamation formula. The same formula appears in 2 Sam 16:16, 1 Kgs 1:25-34, and 2 Kgs 11:12 — the acclamation that publishes the installation to the assembled people and commits them to the king's authority. The shouting of <em>yĕḥî hammelek</em> is the people's covenantal ratification.</p>",
    "25": "<p>Samuel explains to the people <em>mišpaṭ hammalḵûṯ</em> (the rights and duties of the kingship), writes it in a document (<em>bassēp̄er</em>), and deposits it before YHWH. The <em>mišpaṭ hammalḵûṯ</em> is widely associated with Deuteronomy 17:14-20 — the law of the king that limits royal power: no multiplying horses (military buildup), wives (foreign alliances), silver and gold (wealth accumulation), and the requirement to write a copy of the Torah that he reads daily. The deposit &#8220;before YHWH&#8221; places the document in the sanctuary as a covenant witness — the same function served by the Torah deposit beside the ark (Deut 31:26) and treaty tablets in ANE covenant-making contexts.</p>",
    "26": "<p>Saul returns to Gibeah accompanied by &#8220;men of valor&#8221; (<em>ḥayil</em>) whose hearts God had touched (<em>nāgaʿ ʾĕlōhîm bĕlibbām</em>). The formation of a personal guard around the new king is the standard consolidation of royal authority in ANE contexts. The Amarna letters show Canaanite city-kings maintaining standing guards of <em>šu-ut rēši</em> (men of the head/personal guard). David's mighty men (2 Sam 23) represent the mature development of what begins here. The divine authorization — &#8220;hearts God had touched&#8221; — frames the voluntary attachment as Spirit-initiated loyalty, not merely political calculation.</p>",
    "27": "<p>The &#8220;worthless men&#8221; (<em>bĕnê bĕliyyaʿal</em>) who despise Saul and bring him no gift (<em>minḥāh</em>) represent the dissenters from royal authority whose tribute-refusal is a formal act of rejection. In Iron Age politics, bringing a gift to the newly installed ruler was the standard form of political submission and loyalty — tribute-payment acknowledged sovereignty. The Amarna archive documents this protocol extensively: vassal kings bringing gifts to pharaoh as loyalty demonstrations. Withholding gifts from Saul is a deliberate political statement of non-recognition. Saul's silence (<em>wayĕhî kĕmaḥărîš</em>, &#8220;he kept silent&#8221;) is noted as a mark of restraint — he does not retaliate against the dissenters.</p>"
  },
  "11": {
    "1": "<p>Nahash the Ammonite (&#8220;serpent&#8221; in Hebrew) besieges Jabesh-gilead. The Ammonites occupied Transjordanian territory east of Gilead (modern northern Jordan); their expansion westward into Israelite Gilead represents the Transjordanian political pressure that contributed to the demand for a king (1 Sam 12:12). Jabesh-gilead was a significant Israelite settlement in Transjordan, previously associated with the Benjamin war (Judg 21:8-14) — a community with a prior covenantal link to Benjamin. The men of Jabesh's proposal to &#8220;make a treaty&#8221; (<em>kĕrāṯ-lānû ḇĕrîṯ</em>) reflects Iron Age diplomatic practice: besieged cities regularly negotiated surrender terms rather than resisting to annihilation.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Nahash's counter-terms — gouging out the right eye of every man (<em>nĕqar lākem kol-ʿayin yāmîn</em>) as a condition of treaty — represents a well-attested ANE warfare mutilation practice. Eye-gouging appears in Akkadian military annals as a standard punishment for captives and defeated enemies (Sennacherib's annals; Assyrian palace reliefs). The right eye specifically was gouged to impair a soldier's ability to use a shield effectively (the shield covering the left side of the body while fighting). The strategy was to disable the military capacity of the population while leaving them alive as a subjugated workforce. Nahash's stated purpose — &#8220;to bring disgrace on all Israel&#8221; (<em>lĕśûm ḥerpāh ʿal-kol-yiśrāʾēl</em>) — confirms the political symbolism beyond the tactical dimension.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The seven-day delay for sending messengers throughout Israel reflects Iron Age communication realities. Foot messengers covering Israelite territory — from Jabesh-gilead in Transjordan to the central highlands and south — required several days each direction. The seven-day period is both practical (minimum time for a genuine pan-Israelite response) and theologically significant (the standard covenant-action timeframe in OT narrative). Nahash grants the delay because he calculates — correctly, based on Israel's recent disunity — that no effective relief will come. The elders' negotiation buys time while admitting their inability to defend themselves independently.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The messengers' arrival at Gibeah of Saul and the people's communal weeping (<em>wayyiśśĕʾû qôlām wayyiḇkû</em>) reflects the collective grief-response pattern of Iron Age Israelite communities facing military threat. Communal weeping in the gate zone (the public gathering place) was the appropriate public response to crisis — it activated social solidarity and signaled the need for collective action. Saul's absence from the town — he is still working the fields behind his oxen — reflects his failure to yet assume the royal functions the people had just acclaimed him for; he is still a farmer, not yet a king in practice.</p>",
    "5": "<p>Saul returning from the field behind his oxen (<em>ûšāʾûl bāʾ ʾaḥărê habbāqār min-haśśāḏeh</em>) is his last appearance as a farmer; after this episode he is consistently the king in function. Iron Age Israelite agriculture required constant attention — plowing, planting, and harvesting could not be delegated during critical periods. The fact that Saul is plowing immediately after his acclamation as king reveals that the institution of kingship was not yet fully developed: there was no palace, no standing army, no administrative structure. The first king is still a subsistence farmer answering to the agricultural calendar.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The Spirit of God coming powerfully upon Saul (<em>waṯṯiṣlaḥ rûaḥ ʾĕlōhîm ʿal-šāʾûl</em>) at the hearing of the distress-news mirrors the Spirit's coming on the judges (Judg 3:10; 6:34; 14:6). The phrase <em>ṣālaḥ rûaḥ</em> (Spirit came powerfully) is the formula for divine military empowerment in early Israel — it precedes the Spirit-driven violence of Samson (Judg 14:6,19) and the Spirit-driven courage of the judges. Saul's burning anger (<em>wayyi­ḥar ʾappô mĕʾōḏ</em>) is the emotional correlate of the Spirit's coming — a righteous fury at the covenant violation represented by the Ammonite threat to covenant kin.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Saul cuts up a yoke of oxen and sends the pieces throughout Israel with the message: &#8220;Whoever does not march out after Saul and Samuel, this is what will be done to his oxen.&#8221; The cutting of animals and sending the pieces as an oath-threat has deep ANE roots. The covenant-cutting ritual (<em>kāraṯ bĕrîṯ</em>) likely derives from the practice of cutting animals to ratify an oath — both parties walked between the pieces, invoking the same fate on themselves if they violated the covenant (Gen 15:9-17; Jer 34:18-20). Sending the pieces as a threat extends the ritual in an inverse direction: the pieces sent to others means &#8220;this will happen to you if you do not comply.&#8221; The Judges parallel is the Levite sending his concubine's body parts (Judg 19:29) — the same shock-mobilization technique.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The muster at Bezek (in Manasseh, west of the Jordan, opposite Jabesh-gilead) produces 300,000 Israelites and 30,000 from Judah. These numbers follow the pattern of large round numbers in Iron Age military musters — the distinction between Israel (northern/central) and Judah reflects the emerging regional differentiation that will solidify in the divided monarchy. Bezek was a strategic assembly point: its location made rapid crossing of the Jordan to Jabesh-gilead logistically feasible. The muster size, even if schematic, indicates a pan-Israelite military response — the tribal levy system functioning at national scale for the first time under the new king.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The message to the men of Jabesh-gilead — &#8220;by tomorrow at noon you will be rescued&#8221; (<em>mōḥār ṯiḇyaḥ lakem liḵšôṯ haššemeš</em>, lit. by the heat of the sun tomorrow) — uses the temporal formula for military action at midday, the heat of the day when forces would be least expecting attack (cf. 2 Sam 4:5). The Jabesh men's joy at the rescue message (<em>wayyiśmĕḥû ʾanšê yāḇēš</em>) indicates both relief and the activation of the covenant bond: Saul and Samuel represent the covenant people coming to the aid of a covenant community under threat. The promise of rescue by a specific time demonstrates military confidence and prophetic assurance.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The Jabesh men's message to Nahash — &#8220;tomorrow we will come out to you and you may do with us whatever seems good to you&#8221; — is a deceptive compliance designed to prevent Nahash from suspecting the relief force. The deception is presented without moral comment; in Iron Age military ethics, strategic deception of an enemy threatening covenant kin was acceptable. The phrase &#8220;whatever seems good to you&#8221; (<em>kĕkol-haṭṭôḇ bĕʿênêḵā</em>) uses the standard formula of submission to the discretion of a superior — here used as a military feint.</p>",
    "11": "<p>Saul divides his force into three columns attacking in the morning watch (<em>ʾašmōreṯ habbōqer</em> — the period just before dawn, approximately 2-6 AM). Three-column envelopment tactics appear throughout ANE military literature: the strategy maximizes surprise and surrounds the enemy before they can organize a defense. The morning watch attack coincides with the deepest sleep period for an overnight-camped force. The Ammonite rout is described as a complete dispersal — &#8220;no two of them were left together&#8221; (<em>welōʾ-nišʾărû šĕnayim yāḥaḏ</em>) — the formula for total military defeat (Num 14:9; Isa 17:2).</p>",
    "12": "<p>The people's demand to execute the &#8220;worthless men&#8221; who said &#8220;shall Saul reign over us?&#8221; (cf. 10:27) follows the pattern of post-victory justice: military success legitimized the king's authority and made the dissenters' position untenable. In Iron Age Israelite politics, surviving dissenters from a newly acclaimed king whose military victory had just validated his authority were in a vulnerable position — the victory retroactively condemned their opposition. The crowd's willingness to kill them &#8220;on this day&#8221; (<em>bayyôm hazzeh</em>) reflects the heightened emotional state of post-battle celebration.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Saul's response — &#8220;No one shall be put to death today, for today the LORD has given Israel victory&#8221; — is a magnanimity that matches David's later restraint (1 Sam 24-26) and Solomon's initial clemency (1 Kgs 2:36-46). The theological framing (&#8220;YHWH has worked salvation in Israel&#8221; — <em>kî hayyôm ʿāśāh YHWH tĕšûʿāh bĕyiśrāʾēl</em>) redirects the glory from Saul to YHWH — the proper theological interpretation of military success. This moment of restraint and piety represents Saul at his best; the tragedy of his subsequent career lies against this promising beginning.</p>",
    "14": "<p>Samuel's call to go to Gilgal and &#8220;reaffirm (<em>ḥaddēš</em>, renew/make new) the kingship there&#8221; connects this victory to the covenant-renewal site. Gilgal's associations — first Passover in Canaan (Josh 5), circumcision of the wilderness generation (Josh 5:2-9), memorial stones (Josh 4:20-24) — made it the appropriate location for covenantal renewal and installation. Samuel's initiative signals that the victory is the occasion for formalizing what the lot-selection at Mizpah began; the military vindication of Saul's kingship provides the political legitimacy that the lot-casting provided the religious-covenantal legitimacy.</p>",
    "15": "<p>At Gilgal, Saul is made king &#8220;before YHWH&#8221; (<em>lip̄nê YHWH bĕgilgāl</em>), peace offerings are made, and there is great rejoicing. The &#8220;before YHWH&#8221; formula designates a formal covenant-making occasion in the divine presence — the kingship is installed as a covenantal institution, not merely a political arrangement. The peace offerings (<em>šĕlāmîm</em>) seal the covenant between YHWH, the king, and the people — the three-party covenant structure of Israelite kingship theology. The great rejoicing (<em>wayyiśmĕḥû šām šĕmûʾēl wĕkol-ʾanšê yiśrāʾēl</em>) completes the installation narrative on a positive note before Samuel's farewell address complicates the picture.</p>"
  },
  "12": {
    "1": "<p>Samuel's farewell address begins with his affirmation: &#8220;I have listened to you in everything you asked of me and have set a king over you.&#8221; The address follows the <em>rîb</em> (covenant lawsuit) genre — a structured sequence of: (1) summons to covenant witnesses, (2) statement of YHWH's benevolent acts, (3) accusation of covenant violation, (4) call to decision, (5) consequences. Samuel's opening establishes his own fidelity before proceeding to Israel's failure. Parallels include Moses's farewell in Deuteronomy, Joshua's in Josh 24, and the prophetic lawsuits of Micah 6 and Jeremiah 2. The formal genre signals the gravity of what follows.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Samuel's self-description — old and gray, with his sons present — establishes the transition of leadership and the vulnerability of the succession. His claim &#8220;I have led you from my youth until this day&#8221; (<em>wĕʾānōkî hiṯhallakṯî lip̄nêḵem</em>) uses the idiom of consistent covenant service. The presence of his sons is a subtle reminder of the failed succession that precipitated the kingship request (8:1-5). Samuel's sons' corruption is not revisited in the farewell speech — the focus is on Samuel's own integrity, which he will invite the people to challenge.</p>",
    "3": "<p>Samuel's challenge — &#8220;testify against me before YHWH and before his anointed: whose ox have I taken? Whose donkey have I taken? Whom have I defrauded or oppressed?&#8221; — is the formal <em>rîb</em> self-defense, inviting contradiction under oath. The specific items — ox, donkey, bribery (<em>kōp̄er</em>), sandal (<em>naʿal</em>?) — represent the standard categories of corrupt judicial and administrative behavior. The <em>nāgîḏ</em> (designated leader) was obligated to administer justice without corruption; Samuel's challenge establishes his covenantal integrity as the backdrop against which Israel's unfaithfulness will be measured.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The people's threefold denial — &#8220;you have not defrauded us, oppressed us, or taken anything from anyone&#8221; — functions as a formal legal declaration. In ANE legal proceedings, witnesses' unanimous confirmation of the accused's innocence concluded the hearing in the accused's favor. The people's declaration gives Samuel a clean verdict of faithful administration, establishing the moral contrast: the judge who administered faithfully vs. the people who rejected his God. The verdict is publicly proclaimed before &#8220;YHWH and before his anointed&#8221; — the two covenant witnesses.</p>",
    "5": "<p>Samuel's response — &#8220;YHWH and his anointed are witnesses today that you have found nothing in my hand&#8221; — formalizes the legal verdict with divine witness. Invoking YHWH as witness to a declaration called on the highest possible authority to guarantee the truth of the statement; perjury before YHWH was a capital crime in Israelite law (Lev 19:12). The inclusion of &#8220;his anointed&#8221; (<em>ûmĕšîḥô</em>) alongside YHWH as witness establishes the new king as a legitimate covenant party — a theologically significant move that binds Saul to the covenant framework Samuel has just established.</p>",
    "6": "<p>Samuel's historical recital (vv6-12) begins with the foundational salvation: &#8220;It is YHWH who appointed Moses and Aaron and brought your ancestors up from Egypt.&#8221; The Exodus as the constitutive saving act is the universal starting point for Israelite covenant recitals (Deut 26:5-9; Josh 24:2-13; Ps 78, 105-106; Neh 9). By beginning with the Exodus, Samuel locates the present moment within the long arc of YHWH's saving history — the kingship request is not an isolated event but a pattern that can only be assessed within the context of YHWH's consistent faithfulness and Israel's consistent unfaithfulness.</p>",
    "7": "<p>&#8220;Take your stand, so I may lay before you before YHWH all the righteous deeds (<em>ṣiḏqôṯ</em>) of YHWH.&#8221; The <em>ṣiḏqôṯ YHWH</em> (YHWH's righteous acts) are the saving acts that demonstrate his covenantal faithfulness — the term encompasses both justice and deliverance. The lawsuit genre requires the recitation of benefits before the accusation: YHWH's faithfulness establishes the standard against which Israel's unfaithfulness is measured. The formal &#8220;stand still&#8221; (<em>hiṯyaṣṣĕḇû</em>) before the recital positions Israel as the accused before the covenant tribunal.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The Egypt-to-settlement recital compresses centuries of history into a covenant-pattern statement: Jacob went to Egypt, ancestors cried out, YHWH sent Moses and Aaron, YHWH brought them out and settled them in this place. The <em>ṣāʿaq</em> (cry out) verb triggers YHWH's response in both the Exodus (Exod 2:23-24) and the judges cycle (Judg 3:9,15; 6:6-7); the pattern of &#8220;cry out → YHWH sends a deliverer → settlement&#8221; is the covenant-rescue formula of early Israelite theology. Samuel uses the compressed form because he is about to repeat the same pattern for the Judges period, demonstrating the cyclical consistency of both YHWH's faithfulness and Israel's failure.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The judges-period recital names three oppressors: Sisera (commander of Hazor's army, defeated by Deborah and Barak in Judg 4-5), the Philistines (the continuous coastal pressure of the Iron Age I period), and Moab (Eglon in Judg 3:12-30). Each represents a distinct geopolitical threat from the surrounding nations — northern, western, and eastern oppressors respectively. The selection demonstrates the pan-regional scope of Israel's vulnerability when they &#8220;forgot YHWH their God&#8221; (<em>wayyiškĕḥû ʾet-YHWH ʾĕlōhêhem</em>). The forgetting-YHWH formula is the Deuteronomistic diagnosis of covenant failure (Deut 6:12; 8:11-14).</p>",
    "10": "<p>The covenant confession pattern — &#8220;We have sinned, for we forsook YHWH and served the Baals and Ashtaroth&#8221; — is the standard penitential formula of the judges cycle (Judg 10:10; cf. Neh 9:16-37). The Baals (<em>habbĕʿālîm</em>) and Ashtaroth (<em>hāʿaštārôṯ</em>) were the Canaanite agricultural fertility deities whose cults persisted in Israelite areas throughout the Iron Age I-II periods — attested by figurines, inscriptions, and cultic installations at Iron Age Israelite sites. The plural forms indicate the diversity of local manifestations of these deities (Baal of Peor, Baal of Hazor, etc.) rather than a single unified cult.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The deliverers named — Jerubbaal (Gideon), Bedan (otherwise unattested; possibly Barak or Abdon), Jephthah, and Samuel — represent the full range of judge-era deliverers from Ephraim and Transjordan. The inclusion of Samuel himself in the list is remarkable — he presents himself as the last in the line of YHWH's Spirit-empowered deliverers whose sufficiency Israel has now rejected in favor of a human king. The rhetorical force: YHWH sent adequate deliverers each time you cried out; you did not need a king; yet now you demand one anyway.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The kingship request is linked directly to the Ammonite threat — &#8220;when you saw Nahash king of Ammon advancing against you, you said, &#8216;No, we want a king to rule over us&#8217; — even though YHWH your God was your king.&#8221; The theological claim &#8220;YHWH your God is your king&#8221; (<em>waYHWH ʾĕlōhêḵem malḵĕḵem</em>) is the theocratic principle that the monarchy request undermined. ANE treaty texts from the Hittite archives establish the suzerain-vassal structure that Israel's covenant with YHWH occupied; YHWH as &#8220;great king&#8221; (<em>melek gādôl</em>) is the covenant structure that made a human king theologically problematic.</p>",
    "13": "<p>&#8220;Now here is the king you chose and asked for&#8221; (<em>wĕʿattāh hinnēh hammelek ʾăšer bĕḥartem ʾăšer šĕʾēltem</em>). The repetition of &#8220;chose and asked for&#8221; underlines Israel's responsibility for the institution — YHWH did not initiate the kingship; Israel requested it. &#8220;The LORD has set a king over you&#8221; (<em>wĕhinnēh nāṯan YHWH ʿălêḵem melek</em>) simultaneously grants the request and frames it as YHWH's accommodation of Israel's choice rather than his ideal will. The tension between divine accommodation and divine purpose runs through the entire Samuel-Saul-David narrative.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The conditional covenant structure (vv14-15) is the classic Deuteronomic &#8220;if/then&#8221; formulation: if you fear YHWH, serve him, obey, do not rebel — then both you and the king who reigns over you will follow YHWH your God. The king is brought inside the covenant conditionality — his survival and success are tied to Israel's covenant fidelity, not merely his own. This is the theological innovation of Israelite kingship over ANE models: the king is not above the covenant but bound by it (Deut 17:20: &#8220;so that he may reign long over his kingdom, he and his children&#8221; — conditioned on Torah faithfulness).</p>",
    "15": "<p>The negative condition — &#8220;if you do not obey YHWH and rebel against his command, then YHWH's hand will be against you and your king&#8221; (<em>wĕhāyĕṯāh yad-YHWH bākem ûḇăʾăḇîḵem</em>) — reverses the saving-hand formula: the same hand that delivers (Exod 9:3; Deut 2:15) will become the instrument of judgment. The formula &#8220;as it was against your ancestors&#8221; locates the threat within the covenant-discipline pattern already demonstrated in the wilderness and judges periods. The conditional nature of covenant survival for both people and king is the Deuteronomistic framework for evaluating every subsequent reign in Kings.</p>",
    "16": "<p>&#8220;Now then, stand still and see the great thing YHWH is about to do before your eyes.&#8221; The &#8220;stand still and see&#8221; (<em>hiṯyaṣṣĕḇû ûrĕʾû</em>) formula is the theophany-witness command — used at the Red Sea (Exod 14:13: &#8220;stand firm and see the salvation of YHWH&#8221;), at key prophetic demonstrations, and in covenant-renewal contexts. Samuel is about to provide a sign that confirms the theological seriousness of the kingship request — not merely a political speech but a covenantal demonstration backed by divine action in nature.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The wheat harvest (<em>qĕṣîr ḥiṭṭîm</em>) occurred in late May/June in Canaan — the dry season when rain was meteorologically impossible in the eastern Mediterranean climate. Summer storms were unknown; thunder in wheat harvest was a once-in-a-lifetime anomaly that would have been interpreted as divine intervention by all ancient observers. Samuel's announcement — &#8220;I will call on YHWH, and he will send thunder and rain&#8221; — turns an agricultural meteorological impossibility into a prophetic sign. The ANE understanding of weather as directly controlled by divine action (Baal was specifically the storm-deity; YHWH's control of weather is his assertion of sovereignty over Baal's domain) makes this sign theologically pointed.</p>",
    "18": "<p>YHWH sends thunder and rain in response to Samuel's prayer on the day of wheat harvest — confirming both the prophetic word and YHWH's sovereignty over the agricultural calendar. The people's fear (<em>wayyîrĕʾû kol-hāʿām mĕʾōḏ ʾet-YHWH</em>) and their terror of Samuel is the expected covenant response to divine demonstration: the same fear-formula appears at Sinai (Exod 20:18-20) and at every major theophanic moment. The sign achieves its purpose: the people understand that YHWH's power over nature validates Samuel's prophetic authority and the theological weight of the covenant framework he has been articulating.</p>",
    "19": "<p>The people's urgent plea — &#8220;Pray to YHWH your God for your servants so we won't die&#8221; — reflects the ANE understanding that human intermediaries with special divine access were essential for approaching an angry deity. Samuel's role as prophetic intercessor parallels Moses's intercession at every crisis point in the wilderness (Exod 17:11; 32:11-14; Num 14:13-19). The fear that the divine demonstration has triggered is appropriate: YHWH's direct intervention signals covenant seriousness, not merely weather anomaly. The people's recognition that they have sinned in asking for a king (&#8220;we have added to all our other sins the evil of asking for a king&#8221;) is the confession the <em>rîb</em> structure has been designed to elicit.</p>",
    "20": "<p>Samuel's reassurance — &#8220;Do not be afraid. You have committed all this wrong, but do not turn away from YHWH&#8221; — is the prophetic response to genuine covenant penitence: the accusation is confirmed, the sin acknowledged, but the door to restoration remains open. This structure — sin acknowledged, fear not, continue following YHWH — is the pattern of prophetic pastoral care throughout the OT (Isa 41:10-14; Jer 29:10-14). The covenant does not terminate at sin; it persists through repentance and renewed commitment to YHWH's exclusive service.</p>",
    "21": "<p>&#8220;Do not turn away to pursue empty idols (<em>tōhû</em>) that cannot help or save — they are worthless.&#8221; The term <em>tōhû</em> (formlessness/emptiness/nothing) applied to idols carries the creation-theology implication: the same word used for pre-creation chaos (Gen 1:2) characterizes the gods of the nations. They are not merely spiritually inferior but ontologically empty — no substance, no power, no reality. Isa 44:9-20 and Jer 10:3-5 develop the idol-polemic at length; Samuel's brief formulation anticipates the full prophetic critique. The double negation — &#8220;cannot help, cannot save&#8221; — targets the specific functions the people were seeking from substitute loyalties.</p>",
    "22": "<p>The covenant promise: &#8220;YHWH will not abandon his people, because of his great name (<em>bĕʿăḇûr šĕmô haggāḏôl</em>) — it pleased him to make you his own people.&#8221; The divine-name argument for YHWH's continued covenant faithfulness is the theological bedrock beneath prophetic warning: YHWH's reputation (&#8220;name&#8221;) is staked on Israel's existence as his covenant community. Ezek 36:21-23 develops this argument explicitly: YHWH acts &#8220;for the sake of my holy name which you profaned among the nations.&#8221; The covenant cannot terminate simply because Israel sins; YHWH's commitment precedes and conditions Israel's existence as his people.</p>",
    "23": "<p>&#8220;Far be it from me to sin against YHWH by stopping my prayers for you&#8221; — Samuel articulates intercession as prophetic obligation, not optional ministry. The prophet who ceases to pray for the people sins against YHWH — the intercessory function is part of the office. Moses's intercession theology (Exod 32:11-14; Num 14:13-19) is here formalized: the mediating prophet owes the people advocacy before YHWH regardless of their spiritual state. Samuel's commitment to &#8220;teach you the good and right way&#8221; alongside prayer defines the dual prophetic function — intercession before YHWH and instruction of the people — that characterizes the classical prophets.</p>",
    "24": "<p>The farewell's positive summary: &#8220;Only fear YHWH and serve him faithfully with all your heart — consider the great things he has done for you.&#8221; The triad — fear, serve, consider — captures the attitudinal, behavioral, and cognitive dimensions of covenant faithfulness. <em>Yārēʾ</em> (fear) is the reverent acknowledgment of YHWH's sovereign power; <em>ʿāḇaḏ</em> (serve) is the behavioral expression of that acknowledgment; <em>rāʾāh</em> (consider, lit. see) is the reflective engagement with YHWH's saving history that motivates ongoing faithfulness. The Deuteronomic summary command (Deut 10:12-13) uses the same triad: fear, serve, and love YHWH.</p>",
    "25": "<p>The closing warning: &#8220;But if you persist in doing evil, both you and your king will be swept away (<em>tisāpû</em>, from <em>sāp̄āh</em>, to sweep away/consume).&#8221; The word <em>sāp̄āh</em> carries the force of total covenant judgment — the same word used for the sweeping away of Sodom (Gen 18:23-24), the consuming of the guilty in the wilderness rebellion (Num 16:26), and the Assyrian exile (2 Kgs 21:13-14). Samuel closes the address on the note of conditional covenant: the covenant is still operative, YHWH has not abandoned his people, but the consequences of continued unfaithfulness are total — king and people together. The joint fate of king and people is the theological insight that will govern the entire narrative of Kings.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    c = load_comm('context', '1samuel')
    merge_comm(c, CONTEXT)
    save_comm('context', '1samuel', c)
    total = sum(len(v) for v in CONTEXT.values())
    print(f'1samuel mkt-context: wrote {total} verses across ch 9-12')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
